es an "official silence" surrounding the destructive aspects of nationalist sentiments. The second edition of Israel, Diaspora, and the Routes of National Belonging includes a new introduction by the author that builds on her groundbreaking research and reflects on the changes to scholarship since the book’s publication in 2004. Additionally, by exploring the dramatic changes to the region’s politics, Habib ensures that the startlingly honest, theoretically rich, and detailed analysis of her original work continues to be of relevance over a decade later.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIsrael and the diaspora. 0aJewsxIdentity. 0aJewszCanadaxAttitudes toward Israel. 0aJewszUnited StatesxAttitudes toward Israel. 0aJews, AmericanxTravelzIsrael. 0aJews, CanadianxTravelzIsrael. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aIsrael-diaspora relations.  aIsrael.  aJewish.  aNorth American Jewish communities.  adiaspora.  anationalism.  apolitics of Israel.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDTL Humanities 2020z978311073776908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065206240uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148751301640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487513016423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487513016.jpg  a978-3-11-065206-2  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2019b2019  a978-3-11-073776-9  DTL Humanities 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles